Made it a decade. Or just the blink of an eye.⁣
⁣
While I really need to feel free to be happy, at times I’ve let my own fears hold me back from fully exploring that freedom. One thing I greatly feared was speaking in front of others and what other people thought of me. Somewhere around 9 years ago, Sage decided we should film a YouTube video together. At one point we had to stop because I was in tears due to my fear, yet Sage patiently encouraged me to keep at it. While it’s still something I struggle with at times, I love how many people I’ve helped on their running journeys over the years. Thank you for that gift, Sage.⁣
⁣
I love exploring and trying new things, but I can get in my own head about all the reasons as to why I shouldn’t do something. Because of Sage, I’ve traveled all over the world, I’ve climbed mountains that I once thought were past my ability level, learned to ski, and so much more. In that, my sense of freedom has expanded into seemingly limitless possibilities.⁣
⁣
There have been some incredibly sad and challenging moments in the past 10 years. Even the past year has seemed like a lot with lots of doctor visits, medical bills and deciding to sell a dream we had because paying both a mortgage and rent after our condo burned down is a lot to handle. However, I look back at the past 10 years and I’m just so grateful for sharing this adventure called life with Sage. Together we’ve created a company we’re passionate about and such a cool life. We’ve pushed each other to grow as people and to understand the advantages of our personality differences. Sage has taught me to be more playful and spontaneous no matter what’s going on in our lives. We might not have the traditional lives or relationship that other people have after being together for this long, but these years have felt like the adventure of a lifetime. ⁣
⁣
Sage, thanks for being my adventure partner these past 10 years. I’ll always have mountains of love for you.

After my older sister left physical form, I realized that I needed to start enjoying my life more now. We don’t know how long we’ve got or how long the people we love have on this earth. Make time to play no matter what is going on. Have moments together where the intention is purely to have fun together. It doesn’t need to come with the pressure of spending money, perfection or even trying to be romantic. Your cadence is how many steps you take per minute. While some studies suggest it can improve running efficiency, I think the best research on the subject is how it can reduce impact load (or stress) on the lower body caused by running.⁣

⌚To find your cadence you can use the data from many GPS watches or count how many steps you take in 1 minute. I suggest just counting one leg and then multiplying it by 2. Spend more time thinking about how you DO want to feel than how you DON’T want to feel.

I get it. Starting something like a strength workout can be challenging. It’s easy to think about why you don’t feel like it now, how uncomfortable it will be, or everything else you could be doing instead.

But what about if you start thinking about how you do want to feel? It feels wonderful to feel strong. It can be rewarding to get out of your comfort zone. When you’re listening to your favorite songs, strength training can actually be pretty fun.

It’s hard to get started with something if you’re focused on how you don’t want to feel. When you shift your focus to how you do want to feel, starting up gets easier.

You have to be intentional about the mindset you want to bring to the rest of your life as well. 

I'll be posting more mindset tips, so follow along for more strategies that can improve your running and your entire life.

Sometimes I feel like I live in a world where it’s not okay to be imperfect, get things wrong, or have a different opinion. I know that’s not entirely true, but the internet and social media oftentimes make it feel like it is.

I’m someone who genuinely likes most people. I remember telling friends in high school “Focus on the good in people. Everyone has some good in them.” I still truly believe that. However, it’s often hard to accept that not everyone thinks the same way. I see people get into arguments instead of discussions and see others try to tear someone down on social media who they would actually probably like if they were chatting in person. 

As someone who has suffered from social anxiety and doesn’t want to say the wrong thing, speaking is often terrifying. Since I’m human, I’m going to get things wrong or wish I would have said something different at times. If I could, I’d go back and change a lot of YouTube videos, podcasts, reels, etc. But even though I feel like a few people in the world don’t always give others the grace to be imperfect, to make mistakes, or have different thoughts, I want to be someone who does.

I want to be part of creating a culture where everyone feels safe to speak, grow, make mistakes, and to make things better. To do that, I know I have to use my own voice. I have to be willing to be in the arena and to be myself. Sometimes being myself is creating content like this, other times it will be talking about training topics, and I’ll leave room open for all possibilities. 

While it’s okay for me to have fear, letting it hold me back from being myself or fulfilling my purpose is not. The same is true for you.

Strides and hill sprints can be a great way to improve your running economy without taking up any more of your time.

Running economy is like a fuel efficiency measure in a car. A car that has better miles per gallon is more fuel efficient than a car that gets fewer miles per gallon. Instead of fuel, we’re talking about oxygen usage. So simply put, running economy is the amount of oxygen we use to maintain a certain pace.

While strides and sprints can help with better running economy, some people need to be careful implementing them. For instance, if you have Achilles tendon pain or a tight calf muscle, short bursts of speed might make things worse. If you have never done strides, haven't done them for a while, or you’re coming back from a muscle strain or tendon issues, just start with some “pick-ups” (explained in the video) and see how your body responds.

Racing shorter distances is a fantastic way to improve your speed for your longer goal races. 

Now of course specificity matters as well as taking the time to build or maintain a good aerobic base, but there are also a ton of benefits to spending time training for shorter distances. If you follow elite marathoners closely, you’ll often see them race half marathons, 10ks, or even 5ks. Sometimes these races are included in the marathon build, but often there are parts of the year that are dedicated to training specifically for shorter races. 

Depending on the chosen “shorter” race distance and terrain, some benefits may include better-running economy, improving your velocity at VO2 max or lactate threshold, improved biomechanics, or simply just making it so that your marathon or ultra-marathon perceived effort feels a little easier to hold. 

Of course, you can just train for shorter distances without actually racing shorter distances, but you might find that you’re more motivated when you have a race or that you actually like racing shorter distances too.

This paper does a nice job of addressing two common problems that I’ve seen occur when athletes switch to a plant-based diet:

1) Replacing animal products with just carbs instead of things like legumes, tempeh, avocados, nuts, etc.
2) Not considering that plant-based foods are often lower in calories, so more food needs to be consumed and/or higher calorie foods need to be added.

As the paper mentions, we know that there are successful professional and recreational vegan/vegetarian athletes in every sport from football to running, so it’s good to see researchers helping everyone understand that success on a plant-based diet can be achieved for anyone who wishes to pursue it.

Adjusting your hydration plan to meet your sodium and fluid loss as you run can have a huge impact on how well you feel and perform. I’ve had numerous athletes tell me they feel so much better during and after long runs once they started taking more sodium and/or increased their fluid intake. 

On average, people need ~300-600mg of sodium and ~12-24oz of fluids per hour, when partaking in endurance activities. Please keep in mind this is the average. Some people need a little less, but there are also people who need much more than 600mg of sodium per hour. If it’s hot and you’re a heavy sweater, you may need more than 24oz, just keep in mind your stomach can only absorb so many fluids per hour. As always, test out your hydration and nutrition plan during almost every long run, keeping in mind that adjustments may need to be made for heat or altitude.

A Conversation with Wildflowers

Beginning of July
“I’m so glad you’re back! It’s so easy to be happy with you here. I love you!”
“We never left your spirit. We love you!”
(Both laughing as we appreciate each other’s joy in our experience together.)

End of August
“Please don’t go. I need your joy. I love you too much to say goodbye again.”
“In summer we express your joy, beauty, and appreciation for Mother Earth outwardly. Now you must start finding it within and around you in other places. We never really part, we just change. Our love for you is always present.”

“My older sister made her transition from physical back to spirit 3 years ago. I think about her transition a lot this time of year. It’s hard to watch who you love change out of physical form.”
“Like ours, her love is always present. You know she’s there. You feel it. But it’s okay to be sad for the physical loss. Your losses have broken you open so you can be a human wildflower”

Message from the Mountains

There’s nothing you need to do to deserve spending time outside. You don’t need to be at your computer for so many hours to meet society’s standards of working hard so that some time outside seems acceptable and unselfish. You’re not weird for feeling called to spend so much time in the mountains. We see it as “weird” when you ignore your inner guidance to meet the arbitrary expectations of others. You deserve to be outside because you’re part of nature. Because you’re a spirit that chose to come to earth to experience the mountains in physical form.

From the time when the first alpine wild flowers are about to bloom to when the golden leaves fall has always felt sacred to me. It’s a time to just be me and take on less obligations. It’s a time when I fully engage in my growing relationship with nature and try to be one with it all. 

In years past I haven’t fully honored my heart, letting the idea that I need to do more for various reasons get in the way. Some reasons were practical, other reasons were entangled around the ideas of keeping up and being seen as more. None of the reasons were true to my inner knowing. 

This summer and early fall, I honored my heart. I made time for long days in the mountains, with the only purpose of enjoying being outside all day. I could do long runs with 7-10k of vert at high altitudes and feel energized when I was done. I got better at speaking the language of nature and had conversations with the mountains, animals, trees, and wildflowers that made me see and feel the connection and purpose of everything more than I ever have.

While I could easily spend all day outside, running faster was an issue. While I got some FKTs I’m proud of, racing was a challenge when I always worried about how I’d hold up. I’m now in a place where the speed is coming easier, but I know the only reason I’d be doing an ultra this year was to prove to sponsors I’m on my way back up. When I ask my heart what’s best for me right now, the answer is to take my off-season and then do a road/speed block this winter before getting back into trail/ultra racing.

I look back on this entire year and I had so many amazing experiences outside, with loved ones, alone, and with friends. Even if I had raced well, the highlights of this past year would not have included a race. And despite not racing well, I had a wonderful conversation with Topo Athletic today and am extremely excited to be running for such a great company again next year. Thank you @topoathletic for seeing the value in me as a person and athlete.

How My Sister Died (A Lesson on Dying). This is the title of a post my sister, Ray, wrote on our sister Amanda’s transition out of her physical body.

While there was a lot of love in her final days, there was of course an immense amount of pain as well. When I got the text “Call me when you are both together.” (which meant call me when you and Ray are together) from Amanda, I knew exactly what it meant. I was on top of Mount Oxford when the text came through. I immediately had a panic attack, but I knew had to get off the mountain to talk to my sister. The whole way down was a mix of me trying to breathe from ongoing panic attacks, a mess of tears, and determination that I was going to get down to be there for my sisters. That was only the start of what felt like my heart breaking. Whenever I think about it, I still feel my chest tighten and my eyes start to water. Even though I live near Mt Belford and Mt Oxford, I still haven’t been able to go back up.

It’s these thoughts that remind me to enjoy life now and it’s those experiences that broke me open. They constantly push me to follow my heart, even when it feels scary. Those experiences sent me on a path that reconnected with my spirit and reminded me that I am the creator of my life. While 2023 has had some challenges, it has also been one of the most beautiful years of my life. Each season enchanted me and wrapped me up in love and in that love my spirit expanded.

Did I need the pain to allow in more beauty? I’m not sure. However, I do know it reminded me of why my spirit is here as well as that how much love and beauty I allow in and out is always up to me.

-How individualized are your training plans?
Does the coach you’re considering create a runner’s plan completely from scratch or do they have a set training plan for the distance that they tweak for each athlete? 

-How many athletes do you work with?
Do you want to work with a coach who dedicates their time to a small group of athletes or are you okay working with a coach who coaches many athletes at once? 

-Do you have experience coaching people with similar goals as me?
While the answer doesn’t need to be yes, the answer given can give you insight to knowing whether or not a coach will be the right fit for your goals.

-Do you use paces, heart rate, perceived effort or power when prescribing runs? Do you prescribe runs by time or miles/kilometers?
While some coaches use a mix of different metrics, some coaches may prefer to use just one. 

-Will you plan runs around my schedule?
Make sure the coach is willing to work with your schedule and sees you as an entire person with other responsibilities and interests. You don’t want a long run put on a Saturday if that’s your busiest day of the week.

-Can you help me with my mindset during runs, running form, or strength training?
Some coaches may also be able to help you form a more positive mindset around yourself and running. Additionally, some coaches may also have the knowledge to do gait analysis, movement assessments, and design strength programs. If these are important to you, you’ll want to make sure you find a coach with these skills.

-What’s your coaching philosophy?
This is another question that will help you understand if a coach will be the right fit for your specific wants and needs. 

-What will our communication look like and how often do you check training plans?
Will the communication mainly be through comments on your training plan, or are texting, emails, phone calls and video meetings options? Is there a limit to emails or calls?

Running more miles or adding in speed work does not mean you should feel like crap.

Feeling bad means something needs to change. It could be your training, nutrition, sleep, or stress levels. If you look at those things and there’s nothing obvious, consider getting a blood test, talking to a doctor or dietician, or going over your training with a coach. 

When you start building up your mileage or intensity, it’s okay to feel a little tired some days. A little tired means you may feel a small amount of muscle fatigue or it feels nice to sit for a little while. You shouldn’t feel like it’s impacting your ability to focus and get things done or make you unpleasant to be around. Make sure you’re not trying to mask being overly tired with lots of caffeine. You need to be able to hear what your body is telling you. For the most part, you should feel good, like the additional miles or intensity is making you stronger.

Taking the time to do a base phase where you build up your mileage is a key component of endurance training. It can be a great way to start building up for a race, but sometimes it’s not the best option. For instance, if your time to run is before 8 am or after 5 pm, all your winter runs might be dark and cold. If that’s not very enjoyable to you, pushing yourself to run a lot might mentally burn you out before spring comes around. Instead, you could keep your mileage down (if you typically peak at 50 miles per week for a marathon, let’s say ~30-35 miles) and train for a 5k or 10k in February. After that, then you start building up to peak mileage.

From skiing up mountains to using an elliptical at a gym, cross-training is a great way to build your aerobic base. You may do it on top of your runs, or if your body could really use a break from the stress from running, you may choose to cross-train completely for a while. Instead of going by miles (or kilometers), train by time. 

Personally, I found I enjoy winter training most when I run moderate (not high) mileage and ski about 2x per week, which keeps my aerobic base pretty high. I also tend to focus more on road training in winter instead of trails.

With that said, there are still hundreds of “it depends”. It depends on how new you are to running, if you ended 2023 feeling good or mentally and physically tired from running, where you live, where’s your biggest room for improvement, etc. What I can tell you for sure, is that if you’re really struggling to embrace winter running, you should not be trying to run peak mileage right now. You have other options that will still support your goals. Forcing it is not grit, it’s ignoring your joy and what’s best for yourself.
